<br>
Artists are paid in both performance royalties (how often the song is played on the radio and source music - tv, commercial, movie soundtrack, etc) and mechanical royalties. Mechanical royalties are paid on a basis of albums sold (and a number of tracks on that album, up to 11, I believe) and the rates are controlled by a national statutory rate set by Congress. The mechanical royalties are one of the primary sources of income for most musicians. <br>
<br>
(Of course, a lot of musicians - writers in particular - would die to have a soundtrack song for a popular movie, not only for the publicity, but each showing, video rental, etc. produces performance royalties for source music, plus residuals contracted out from the actual soundtrack sales which I believe are handed differently.)<br>
<br>
There are a number of splits where the money goes, depending on the writer, the publisher, the performer, etc. Your average $15 CD (I know, they're more expensive now, but I'm working from dated knowledge) produces about $11.15 worth of revenue that is considered for royalty purposes. The average mechanical royalty rate after the deductions and splits and whatnot (and assuming the performer is also the writer) is around 10%. So your average artist is making about $1.25 (rounding up a bit for easy math or so per album.<br>
<br>
So downloading eliminates X% of how many albums they sell, but if you look a little closer, any given act has a huge debt to pay off. Most artists don't break even until they sell almost 500,000 albums. At that point, they haven't made any money at all. (Also side note, only about 10% of acts actually make back the advance - promotion, recording, publishing, printing - of an album. It's unfortunate but the world of good music rides on the coattails of Garth Brooks, Janet Jackson, and The Backstreat Boys...) <br>
<br>
If they're given an advance for a video as well, it may take an artist closer to selling 1,000,000 copies before they hit the break even point (of which only 900,000 are considered because of age-old traditions of not getting paid for albums that broke in shipment. Something that doesn't happen hardly at all with CD's as opposed to vinyl).<br>
<br>
The performance royalties are a long-term investment, and risky at best. These also go almost exclusively to the songwriter, or the holder of the rights to those songs, though, which is why you see the Beatles catalogue going for millions of dollars. It's a risky venture, without one killer song on an album, the performance royalties are going to be a pittance compared to the mechanical royalties.<br>
<br>
So yes, in fact, the artists are being ripped off by the record industry to a massive degree. The artist, on a good contract with a good fanbase is pulling down $1.50 per CD or so (oh yeah, then off profits, deduct 20% for management, then split it between the 4-5 members of the band...), only the songwriter (which is sometimes the entire band, but not always) is pulling down the performance royalties. The record companies are making $3-6 per album. <br>
<br>
But it's really hard to blame the artist in that situation. They are definitely under the thumb of the big media companies, but the big media companies are the only ones who guarantee they even get the pittance of profit they do get... the RIAA is, by virtue of their greed in maintaining their $3-6 per album the ones making sure and fighting for the artist's right to get paid (even less) for their own material. So as much as I think Metallica's gone off the deep end, supporting the RIAA is not an illogical position for them or any other act.<br>
<br>
Downloading music is, ultimately, stealing from the artist - at least those artists who are published by the RIAA. It may be an incredible tool for getting name recognition and distribution out there for lesser known artists who don't currently have record contracts, but that remains to be proven as an effective advertising method. Donwloading music hurts the artist in what I would consider collateral damage at something that, free music aside, is primarily directed at hurting the big music companies.<br>
<br>
The sad fact is, because so much of an artist's profit is tied up in mechanical royalties, and the deals negotiated by the RIAA with legal systems like Apple's new music download system, actually put more money in the pockets of the RIAA and less in the hands of the artists than if we're forced to buy albums containing all of their material.<br>
<br>
Sorta a non-partisan view on the whole thing, really. I've never actually downloaded illegal music, just samples and the stuff that artists and labels provide free. And when someone loans me a CD, if I like it, I'll buy a copy. And suing the customer is not exactly the best politic thing to do, but with everything from governmental regulation to derrision of the whole idea of 'intellectual property' and wanting something for nothing, there's a lot more that needs to change than just stopping downloading.<br>
<br>
Downloading won't stop, but the RIAA is left with few alternatives. And the artist left with fewer alternatives still than to let the RIAA help them get what they are due via their contracts. It's a sad circle, but major reform of the entire industry will need to take place before any of it budges at all...<br>
<br>
Sorta depressing when you think about it.<br>
<br>
