 illegal to steal it, I fully agree.  Unfortuantely, I think art belongs to the artist, ONLY, and if it becomes an industry, you are taking form the artist and the art-form itself.  When Metallica went from Mega-force to Capitol, it was in their best financial intereast to begin supporting the comercialization of their music.  Maybe you don't notice the drop in the quality of their music, I do.  <br>
I will be one to tell you that if you download music you are stealing it, becasue you are.  At the same time, I will not tell you to stop, because this art was TAKEN from the creators by the producers.  I have told bands my theories of the music industry; they hug me for it.  Living right outside of Detroit, Michigan, you can imagine how many hugs that is.  I will buy it from them, but I won't buy it from Capitol.  The problem ISN'T that the artists can't do it on their own... the problem is that they can't compete with the mega-corps.  My solution isn't to try to bring down the corps, that's impossible.  Mine is a very personal solution in that I will only buy from the artist.<br>
<br>
The simple truth is that you can't download a show.  When you go to a show and they are selling their self produced CD, it is reasonably priced, and you are buying DIRECTLY from the artist.  I REFUSE to pay Capitol for Joan Ridel's songs, I will pay Joan directly... and have.  <br>
In this day and age, you can not tell me that bands can not market their own music.  Sure, the industry may make it easier, but their methods are immoral and a stain on the art form.  Stealing IS wrong, and downloading music IS stealing it from the industry, but this is a case where I will just turn my head and pretend I never saw you do it. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://guildmagic.com/character.cfm?ID=316564" target="top">Tib</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
