<br>
It's all about volume. 30 years ago, maybe you made a copy of your friend's new Blue Oyster Cult record and listened to it. Maybe your brother made a copy of that tape. It rarely went much beyond that. Nowadays, you can post a song online and it can be downloaded literally downloaded millions of times. Those copies can then be further downloaded millions more times. It is significantly different.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You think it's &quot;wrong&quot; that the artists don't get enough of the sticker price? So fucking what. That's down to them to negotiate with their record company. None of your damn business.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Unfortunately, it doesn't work that way. Either the artist accepts the deal they are offered, or they get <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>NO</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> deal. There is no negotiating. The record labels have the resources to dictate terms to new artists. Maybe an estabilished artist can negotiate a bigger piece of the pie, but by and large, it's a &quot;take it or leave it&quot; situation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I know that sounds ignorant, but Grand Theft is MUCH different.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You can equate downloading 1 mp3 more accurately with stealing a chocolate bar. What's happening now, however, is more like people walking off with the entire factory. It is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>NOT</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> different. People are downloading <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>MILLIONS</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of songs per day. That <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>IS</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> grand theft.<br>
<br>
Now, speaking as an unsigned musician, I say:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>DOWN WITH THE RIAA</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
