<br>
Yes, I am involved in the music industry in some way, but I won't tell you how because it's none of your damn business! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So my income aside, and in my opinion, here is why downloading music is a bad idea:<br>
<br>
1)  Artist - The artist recieves what is called a &quot;Royalty&quot; from sales of their ART (&lt;notice how I capatalized ART&gt;).  They royalty that they recieve per each sale of their ART is significantly less than you can possibly comprehend or imagine.  <br>
<br>
Also, based on reports from a thing called &quot;Soundscan&quot;, an Artist recieves another &quot;Royalty&quot; from each time their song is played on the radio.  This is also significantly less than you can possibly imagine.<br>
<br>
Finally, an artist recieves income from Concert Tours and Venue sales, endorsments (like Pepsi), and through personal appearances.  This is where the artist makes the bulk of their capital.<br>
<br>
In order for an artist to be successful, to actually make money for their ART, they must be able to successfully promote themselves.  Promotion costs money.  There are posters, advertising, travel, personal expenses, etc.  In order to promote yourself successfully, it takes money.  A lot of money.  <br>
<br>
Most Artists cannot do this on their own (for it is far, far too expensive) so they rely on a recording company to foot the bill.  The recording company notices the saleability of an artist, their ability to generate radio airplay (most important), and ticket sales from tours.  They give the Artist and advance (which is like a loan).  Usually, it is just enough to get the artist on track to make a decent living.<br>
<br>
Once the artist signs the contract, the advance money starts decreasing rapidly.  There are expenses (like using a professional recording studio to record their album at 1000's of dollars an hour), distribution (I will get back to this), promotion, and tour expenses (like that bus you see them riding around in - which may seem extravagant to you but it's their home for a year or more).<br>
<br>
What a record company will do is take care of all of this for the artist in the hope that the artist will get significant radio play, which turns into sales, which makes people buy tickets for their live shows.  Once the artist has paid off the Advance, then they start generating income for themselves, and most times only if they make significant sales.<br>
<br>
Otherwise, the record company puts them on the road, where they become &quot;Road Dogs&quot;.  A Road Dog will stay on the road, away from their families, playing the same songs night after night until their advance is paid.  Then the record company will usually drop their contract.  Sound evil?  Well, perhaps, but this is a business and just like things that don't sell don't get manufactured, so artists get dropped.<br>
<br>
If you are a lucky one (which by the way is a very low percentage of ALL the artists that get signed to a Major record label), then maybe you start making your own money.  Maybe you get another deal to make 2 or 3 more records.  At this point you have proved your saleability and the recording company will use their market saavy to help you sell more.  Many artists (like Prince) look at this as slavery.  He may be right, but to the industry it's good business practice. <br>
<br>
Most artists suffer a massive amount before they get lucky.  Many more wither up and die away, or become local acts again and make a few thousand dollars a year.<br>
<br>
2) Record Companies - Take all the risk with a new artist.  Often times the record company sink hundred of thousands of dollars into an Artist who just doesn't have appeal, and must make up for these losses with Artists that do. It's a very difficult and complex &quot;game&quot; for the record company to figure out what may or may not sell.<br>
<br>
A record company manufactures a CD.  I won't tell you how much it costs, but it is very cheap.  Then they put an insert (art) into it, promote it, distribute it, and calculate royalties.  To do all of these tasks takes employees.  Employees are an expense.  They then sell it to a distributor at a cost (which is a small (and I do mean small) percentage of what you pay for a CD at the store).  The distributor tacks on their markup (they have employees too), and the record store tacks on theirs...and thus a CD that cost less than the change you have in your sofa to make a CD that costs you $15 or more at the store.<br>
<br>
When Soundscan reports to the Record Company that a radio station has played a single, they collect a fee from the radio station.  The radio station pays the fee through advertising.  The record company collects this fee and pays the artist their royalty and keeps the rest.  Again, this is far less significant than you can imagine.  The rest of the income is made through endorsments (because likely the Record Company has rights to an artist's catalogue), and other general revenue.  By this time, they hope they can make a profit to sign more artists and generate more revenue.  Often times they lose, sometimes they break even, even more rarely a U2 comes along and makes them a large enough profit to cover their other losses - and like any business make a profit.<br>
<br>
So, in a nutshell, and far more complicated than I can explain in this meagar space, when you download music, you are killing the industry.  When a record company sells 200,000 copies of an album that previously would have sold 1,000,000, the Artist makes less, the record company makes less, and the Artist is less likely to make another record, nor is the record company likely to re-sign them.<br>
<br>
But, you are killing an evil, evil capatalistic corporate machine!  Yes, perhaps.  But I submit this.  When nobody is willing to put money into a dying business, when you go to the record store to buy CD's and the shelves are empty, when you turn on your radio to only find channel after channel of &quot;Rush Limbaugh&quot;, then will you blame Napster, Kazaa, and other music downloading companies?  When you can't find a great piece of music through all of the trash (go to MP3.COM if you don't believe that there is a bunch of trash out there), how long will your word of mouth campaign carry it, if it's not on the radio and not promotable but through the internet.<br>
<br>
And did you ever wonder why most radio stations play the same crap over and over and over?  Because they know that it's something that they can make revenue on...not because it's any better than anything else.<br>
<br>
And before you go about thinking that you will support your local &quot;Jimmy Jam and the Freedom Band&quot; think about how difficult it is for an artist to fill such a venue every single night (because remember, that is how they get paid, by the number of people that show up).  Think about how unlikely a club owner would be willing to book an act into their venue when 2 people show up and buy 2 beers.  Most people have lives.  Most people can't show up every night.  Most artists can't afford to sustain themselves this way.<br>
<br>
Worst of all is the fellow who is supporting a family working in a Record Company mail room who has to go tell his kids that he got laid off and has to find a new job, because illegal downloading has cost the record companies as a whole huge profits and they can't afford him any more.<br>
<br>
You are not hurting an evil, corrupt company, because like most companies they will file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy and become extinct. You are hurting real people with real dreams and aspirations, and if that is worth your concience and stealing music from the internet, then go for it.....just remember what I said in a year.  You are hurting much, much more than Metallica, and although I don't necessarily agree with a lot of what Lars says, I do respect him very much for protecting the little guy.<br>
<br>
Finally, imagine if you made a cool widget.  And someone went into wal-mart and stole all your widgets.  And it cost you way more to make widgets than you were getting money from them.  How long would you continute to make them?  How long before you would cry &quot;foul&quot; and try to reduce your losses?<br>
<br>
And I am sure that I will be met with a barrage of insults, tiraids, and hate....and that's fine.  You are entitled to your opinion on the matter.  I am just a person most of you don't know.  But I hope that these words mean something to someone.<br>
<br>
P.S.  The RIAA, by the way, is paid by the 5 major record labels to protect the interests of the recording community, and do not directly make money from the sales of records....just so you know. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thedosiusdreamtwister>Thedosius Dreamtwister</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.rogers.com/shadowgovernment01/thedhead.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 287<br> <font color=#330000>(7/28/03 10:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=883.topic&index=55>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: </span><hr size=1> That begs 2 questions:<br>
