<br>
Most 'musicians' and even fewer songwriters can make a living. The fact is, new songwriters are dependant on the big multi-million-dollar-in-the-bank acts to even get noticed.<br>
<br>
Okay, record execs tend to make money... they're not exactly in the same class as the other two you've listed. Big acts are, but big acts are the top 1% of all popular music acts and probably the top .0001% of all musicians.<br>
<br>
And just because person A makes more money than person B, it doesn't give person B any more right to person A's stuff. Here's another tack - why doesn't person B go out and get a second job (or likely a first one) so they can afford what they want that person A has? Why can't, say, person B 'save up' their own damned money so they can buy something?<br>
<br>
Shoe, meet other foot.<br>
<br>
And regardless of how noble the cause, Robin Hood was still a crook.<br>
<br>
But you're right. They haven't found a solution. There won't be a solution because it sits intrinsically with the honesty of the common man.<br>
<br>
There's no hope for that on a wide scale.<br>
